Data encoding is the process of converting information into a format that computers can store, process, and transmit. Encoding ensures that data is interpreted consistently across different systems and devices.

Why Encoding is Needed

Computers only understand binary data, but humans use letters, numbers, and symbols. Encoding provides a standard way to represent this information digitally.

For example:

A → 65 → 01000001
ASCII

ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange) is one of the earliest character encoding standards.

It assigns numerical values to characters.

Examples:

A = 65
B = 66
a = 97

ASCII uses 7 bits and supports 128 characters.

Unicode

Unicode was developed to support characters from many different languages and writing systems.

Benefits:

Supports thousands of characters
Allows global communication
Standard across modern systems
UTF-8

UTF-8 is the most widely used Unicode encoding format.

Features:

Compatible with ASCII
Efficient storage
Used extensively on websites and modern applications
Base64 Encoding

Base64 converts binary data into readable text using letters, numbers, and symbols.

Common uses:

Email attachments
Web applications
Data transmission

Base64 is encoding, not encryption. Encoded data can easily be decoded back to its original form.

Why it maaters in cybersecurity:

Security professionals encounter encoded data when:

Analyzing web traffic
Investigating malware
Examining logs
Working with APIs and authentication tokens

Understanding encoding helps distinguish between encoded, encrypted, and hashed data.

Key Takeaways:
Encoding converts data into a standard format for storage and transmission.
ASCII and Unicode are common character encoding standards.
UTF-8 is the most widely used encoding format today.
Base64 is commonly used to represent binary data as text.
Encoding is not the same as encryption.
